🎤 Interview Question

You are given an employee DataFrame with the following columns:

emp_id, email, phone

Write PySpark code to perform the following tasks:

1. Extract the first 5 characters from the email column into a new column named email_prefix.


2. Find the position of "@" in the email column and store it in a new column named at_position.


3. Remove all "-" (hyphens) from the phone column and store the cleaned value in clean_phone.


4. Display the updated DataFrame.




---

📊 Input Dataset

emp_id	email	phone

101	john.doe@gmail.com	98765-43210
102	alice@yahoo.com	91234-56789
103	bob@company.com	99887-66554
104	sam@test.org	90123-45678
105	david@gmail.com	95555-11122



---

✅ Expected Output

emp_id	email_prefix	at_position	clean_phone

101	john.	9	9876543210
102	alice	6	9123456789
103	bob@c	4	9988766554
104	sam@t	4	9012345678
105	david	6	9555511122



---

✅ Recommended Solution

from pyspark.sql.functions import col, substring, instr, regexp_replace

df = (
    df.withColumn(
        "email_prefix",
        substring(col("email"), 1, 5)
    )
    .withColumn(
        "at_position",
        instr(col("email"), "@")
    )
    .withColumn(
        "clean_phone",
        regexp_replace(col("phone"), "-", "")
    )
)

df.show()


---

⭐ Alternative Solution

Using SQL expressions:

from pyspark.sql.functions import expr

df = (
    df.withColumn(
        "email_prefix",
        expr("substring(email, 1, 5)")
    )
    .withColumn(
        "at_position",
        expr("instr(email, '@')")
    )
    .withColumn(
        "clean_phone",
        expr("replace(phone, '-', '')")
    )
)

df.show()


